Used Cars Price Prediction¶

  • What is the intended goal?

  • What are the key questions that need to be answered?

The problem formulation:¶

  • What is it that we are trying to solve using data science?

Problem Summary

With the data provided, Cars4U is looking to build a model that can accurately predict the current price of a vehicle. More used cars were bought in 2018-2019 than new cars, and Cars4U is looking to capitalize on the growing market. Unlike new cars, whose price is decided by the OEM, used cars have many different aspects that determine their price. Used car prices are affected by supply and demand along with their own attributes. Cars4U would like to use this model to find deals on used cars that will entice customers into buying.

Data Dictionary¶

S.No. : Serial Number

Name : Name of the car which includes Brand name and Model name

Location : The location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase (Cities)

Year : Manufacturing year of the car

Kilometers_driven : The total kilometers driven in the car by the previous owner(s) in KM

Fuel_Type : The type of fuel used by the car (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)

Transmission : The type of transmission used by the car (Automatic / Manual)

Owner : Type of ownership

Mileage : The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg

Engine : The displacement volume of the engine in CC

Power : The maximum power of the engine in bhp

Seats : The number of seats in the car

New_Price : The price of a new car of the same model in INR 100,000

Price : The price of the used car in INR 100,000 (Target Variable)

#Function to plot a boxplot and histogram along the same scale
def histogram_boxplot(df, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows = 2,      # Number of rows of the subplot grid = 2
        sharex = True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw = {"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize = figsize,
    )                   # Creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(data = df, x = feature, ax = ax_box2, showmeans = True, color = "violet"
    )                   # Boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of    #the column
    sns.histplot(
        data = df, x = feature, kde = kde, ax = ax_hist2, bins = bins, palette = "winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data = df, x = feature, kde = kde, ax = ax_hist2
    )                   # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        df[feature].mean(), color = "green", linestyle = "--"
    )                   # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        df[feature].median(), color = "black", linestyle = "-"
    )                   # Add median to the histogram

# Function to create labeled barplots

def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc = False, n = None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])            # Length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize = (count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize = (n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation = 90, fontsize = 15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data = data,
        x = feature,
        palette = "Paired",
        order = data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )                              # Percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()         # Count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # Width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()                 # Height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha = "center",
            va = "center",
            size = 12,
            xytext = (0, 5),
            textcoords = "offset points",
        )                                 # Annotate the percentage

    plt.show()                            # Show the plot

Feature Engineering¶

Think about it: The Name column in the current format might not be very useful in our analysis. Since the name contains both the brand name and the model name of the vehicle, the column would have too many unique values to be useful in prediction. Can we extract that information from that column?

  • Hint: With 2041 unique names, car names are not going to be great predictors of the price in our current data. But we can process this column to extract important information for example brand name.
In [64]:

2041

# Extract Brand Names
df["Brand"] = df["Name"].apply(lambda x: x.split(" ")[0].lower())

    • Code below is used to see the RMSE, MAE, R-squared, Adj. R-squared, and MAPE values.
    In [148]:
    from sklearn.metrics import r2_score,mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error
# Function to compute adjusted R-squared
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# Function to compute MAPE
def mape_score(targets, predictions):
    return np.mean(np.abs(targets - predictions) / targets) * 100


# Function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance

    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    pred = model.predict(predictors)                  # Predict using the independent variables
    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)                       # To compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)    # To compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # To compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)           # To compute MAE
    mape = mape_score(target, pred)                   # To compute MAPE

    # Creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
            "MAPE": mape,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

    Tuning

    In [180]:
    #Define parameters for the grid search
param_grid = {
    'criterion': ['mse', 'mae', 'friedman_mse', 'poisson'],
    'splitter': ['best', 'random'],
    'max_depth': [None, 5, 10, 15, 20],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4],}

    Criterion is used to measure the quality of a split.

    • MSE measures teh variance of teh target variable.
    • MAE measures the mean absolute difference between predicted and actual values.
    • Friedman MSE is a variant of mse and uses friedman's gradient boosting.
    • Poisson is used for count regression.

    Splitter determines the strategy used to choose the split at each node.

    • Best is chosen by the criteria.
    • Random - the best split is chosen randomly.

    Max depth sets the depth of the decision tree. This can help with model complexity and overfitting.

    • None means the tree will expand until all leaves are pure.
    • 5,10,15,20 restrict the max depth to these values.

    Min samples split sets the minimum number of samples required to split a node. This helps with overfitting.

    • 2,5,10 represent the minimum number of samples required for a node to split.

    Min samples leaf sets the minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node. This helps with overfitting.

    • 1,2,4 represent the minimum number of samples required for a leaf node.

    Conclusions and Recommendations¶

    1. Comparison of various techniques and their relative performance based on chosen Metric (Measure of success):

    • How do different techniques perform? Which one is performing relatively better? Is there scope to improve the performance further?

    Executive Summary

    The used car market exhibits complexities not seen in the new car market, and Cars4U is looking to devise profitable strategies to maximize their returns. This project proposed the Random Forest Model for the prediction and forecasting of used cars on the market in 2018-2019. Random Forest was selected after data cleansing, feature engineering, and model optimization. The four main features this model considers are the price for the new models of the vehicle, the year of the vehicle, the maximum power of the engine in BHP, and the kilometers driven. The Random Forest Model was selected out of 6 different models, and was slightly overfitting. It has a 93% predictive performance with an error of around 15% on the test data.

    This model did run into some limitations. There were many unique values for the models of the vehicles, and five of the fourteen columns had missing values. The dataset only contained two electric vehicles (EV), and with the shift in manufacturers making more EVs, this model will need to be updated when there are more used EVs on the market. Depending on future governmental policies and available charging infrastructure, there may be more of a market for EVs and less for diesel and petrol vehicles, which make up 99% of the data.

    2. Refined insights:

    • What are the most meaningful insights relevant to the problem?

    While Random Forest did a good job predicting the price for vehicles, there are some other features to consider. Only brand was considered when creating this model. The model type was left out of the data set as it had too many unique values. It would be worth looking into all the model names and seeing if this will help classify more of them together. Brands such as Bentley, Lamborghini, and Porsche had 20 vehicles in the data set but may have helped skew the price to the right since they are more high-end vehicles. If these brands are not going to be considered when buying vehicles, it may be worth removing them from the dataset.

    It is also worth looking into location, as Coimbatore and Bangalore had higher priced vehicles. The residents there may have a higher net worth and may be willing to pay for more expensive vehicles.

    This data set also only contained 2 EVs. Car manufacturers are producing more EVs, which means in the coming years their will be more used EVs available. This may affect the price for vehicles that use Petrol or Diesel (99% of the data) since they may become less desirable.

    71% of the vehicles included the data set were manual, and this may also negatively impact prices since most vehicles being produced are automatic.

    It is also worth tracking the trend of people buying used or new vehicles. If more and more people are buying used vehicles, this may affect the pricing and supply of new vehicles being produced.

    Two other pieces of valuable information would be the accident history and the current shape the vehicle is in. People are less inclined to buy used vehicles that are in bad shape and have had a severe accident in its history.

    • This dataset had a lot of missing values. I think it would be beneficial to have more complete data.
    • It would probably also be helpful to have more vehicles in the dataset.
    • The models from Name had too many unique values. There may be a better way to group those.
    • Certain car brands like Bentley or lamborghini could probably be removed since both of these cars are much more expensive than others and made up for very little of the data.
    • Tuning the other 4 ML Models could have helped produce better results.

    3. Proposal for the final solution design:

    • What model do you propose to be adopted? Why is this the best solution to adopt?

    Six different models were created for Cars4U. After some hyperparameter tuning, it was found that the best model was Random Forest. The other five models, from best to worst, were Bagging, Decision Tree, Ridge Regression, Linear Regression, and Lasso Regression. Of these 6 models, only Random Forest and Decision Tree had tuning done. The other models may have performed better with feature engineering, and that is something to consider in the future. Their original scores did not show much promise, and that is why they were not evaluated farther.

    I would propose the Tuned Random Forest Model. Overall it performed the best on the training and testing data set. It is slightly overfitting.

    For training it has:

    • Has an average prediction error of 1.5 for the training data set.
    • .54 error on the predicted and actual value.
    • Explains around 98% of the variance in the training data.
    • Around 98% predictive performance.
    • Model prediction on the training data has an error of around 6%.

    For test it has:

    • Has an average prediction error of 2.7 for the testing data set.
    • 1.3 error on the predicted and actual value.
    • Explains around 93% of the variance in the training data.
    • Around 93% predictive performance.
    • Model prediction on the testing data has an error of around 15%.
